1
00:02:14,901 --> 00:02:19,429
<i>Don't let it bother you</i>
<i>When things go wrong</i>

2
00:02:19,606 --> 00:02:23,872
<i>If you're glum, just hum</i>
<i>And some good luck will come along</i>

3
00:02:24,878 --> 00:02:29,406
<i>Don't let it bother you</i>
<i>If now and then</i>

4
00:02:29,582 --> 00:02:34,212
<i>You may stumble, never grumble</i>
<i>Count from one to 10</i>

5
00:02:34,387 --> 00:02:39,347
- A</i> <i>frown is a smile upside down</i>
- <i>So turn that frown upside down</i>

6
00:02:39,526 --> 00:02:44,896
<i>And smile</i>
<i>And sing oh-la-la-la</i>

7
00:02:45,064 --> 00:02:49,558
<i>Don't let it bother you</i>
<i>If skies are gray</i>

8
00:02:49,736 --> 00:02:51,704
<i>Learn to grin</i>
<i>And take it on the chin</i>

9
00:02:51,871 --> 00:02:54,396
<i>Then everything will be okay</i>

10
00:03:55,168 --> 00:03:58,399
Oh, it's no use, Guy.
Mine has housemaid's knee.

11
00:03:58,571 --> 00:04:00,129
Don't be discouraged, Egbert.

12
00:04:00,306 --> 00:04:04,037
I think you show distinct tendencies
towards terpsichorean excellence.

13
00:04:04,210 --> 00:04:06,770
You think so, really?
You know, as a matter of fact...

14
00:04:06,946 --> 00:04:11,042
...my inner soul has always yearned
to express itself in the dance.

15
00:04:11,217 --> 00:04:14,380
- lf you were I, what would you do?
- Stick to law.

16
00:04:19,592 --> 00:04:22,254
Spoken like a real native.
Do you recognize it?

17
00:04:22,428 --> 00:04:23,918
No.

18
00:04:24,831 --> 00:04:27,391
What? Oh, yes.

19
00:04:27,567 --> 00:04:31,298
Oh, my, Guy,
this is an expensive place here.

20
00:04:38,077 --> 00:04:40,978
Guy, in the excitement of changing
my clothes on that train...

21
00:04:41,147 --> 00:04:42,944
...I left my wallet in that other suit.

22
00:04:43,116 --> 00:04:45,949
Egbert, what would you do without me?

23
00:04:48,321 --> 00:04:50,084
I mean to say...

24
00:04:55,194 --> 00:04:57,788
I've been in America
for several months with my friend.

25
00:04:57,964 --> 00:05:02,128
We're passing through Paris on our way
to London. We're taking the boat tomorrow.

26
00:05:06,072 --> 00:05:08,438
I am the proprietor.
What can I do for you?

27
00:05:08,608 --> 00:05:12,135
Well, I'm afraid we'll have to mail you
the amount of the check.

28
00:05:12,545 --> 00:05:15,605
Well, monsieur, I do not know you.

29
00:05:15,948 --> 00:05:18,416
This gentleman's father
is Sir Frederick Fitzgerald...

30
00:05:18,584 --> 00:05:20,677
...the distinguished London attorney.

31
00:05:20,853 --> 00:05:23,947
Yes, and I'm a lawyer too.

32
00:05:24,123 --> 00:05:25,784
You, monsieur?

33
00:05:28,895 --> 00:05:31,227
My friend here is Guy Holden,
the American dancer.

34
00:05:31,397 --> 00:05:34,230
Musical comedy and whatnot.
Certainly you've heard of Holden.

35
00:05:34,400 --> 00:05:37,392
Oh, yes, I have heard of Guy Holden.

36
00:05:37,570 --> 00:05:40,937
But, monsieur, have you any means
of identification?

37
00:05:42,108 --> 00:05:45,100
Well, you see, we...

38
00:05:45,278 --> 00:05:49,112
Left them in the other suit.
Oh, yes, yes, yes.

39
00:05:50,083 --> 00:05:52,210
Well, I...

40
00:05:52,385 --> 00:05:53,909
I have it, I have it.

41
00:05:54,087 --> 00:05:57,022
Look here, old chap,
if my friend dances like Guy Holden...

42
00:05:57,190 --> 00:05:59,920
...that proves he is Guy Holden,
doesn't it?

43
00:06:01,861 --> 00:06:04,091
Go ahead, Guy, dash them off
a bit of a minuet...

44
00:06:04,263 --> 00:06:05,787
...or a polka or a schottische.

45
00:06:05,965 --> 00:06:10,231
Now, wait a minute, I'm on my vacation.
I'm not going to do any dancing.

46
00:06:11,537 --> 00:06:14,404
I've heard they make you
wash dishes in Paris.

47
00:06:25,218 --> 00:06:26,515
There you are.

48
00:06:28,688 --> 00:06:30,212
That means nothing.

49
00:06:30,890 --> 00:06:32,414
Then you try it.

50
00:06:33,893 --> 00:06:36,123
Suppose you do it over there.

51
00:06:36,796 --> 00:06:39,856
- With all these people around?
- Well, if you are Guy Holden...

52
00:06:40,032 --> 00:06:42,330
...people should not disturb you.

53
00:06:42,502 --> 00:06:43,901
No.

54
00:06:46,205 --> 00:06:49,800
French cooking must make the dishes
very difficult to wash.

55
00:08:15,361 --> 00:08:18,159
Guy, never mind.

56
00:08:20,833 --> 00:08:22,266
Thank you.

57
00:08:47,627 --> 00:08:51,893
Mr. Fitzgerald. Mr. Fitzgerald.

58
00:08:52,064 --> 00:08:54,464
Mr. Fitzgerald.

59
00:08:54,634 --> 00:08:57,000
- Mr. Fitzgerald.
- Who is it? What's the matter?

60
00:08:57,169 --> 00:08:58,261
What do you want?

61
00:08:58,437 --> 00:08:59,665
- Mr. Fitzgerald?
- Yes.

62
00:08:59,839 --> 00:09:02,205
- Mr. Pinky Fitzgerald?
- Yes.

63
00:09:02,375 --> 00:09:04,707
Pinky? That's the first time
I've heard that one.

64
00:09:05,311 --> 00:09:07,677
Must be from Father.
He's always called me Pinky.

65
00:09:07,847 --> 00:09:12,250
Ever since I was a golden-haired little tot
paddling about in pale-pink pajamas.

66
00:09:12,418 --> 00:09:14,386
What do you want?
Tip that boy, will you?

67
00:09:14,554 --> 00:09:17,022
Read that for me.
I'm all involved here, Guy, please.

68
00:09:17,189 --> 00:09:19,419
- Thank you, governor.
- Right you are.

69
00:09:20,026 --> 00:09:22,654
Yes, it's from your father. He says:

70
00:09:22,828 --> 00:09:27,322
"Leaving for Scotland. Stop.
Take charge of office in my absence. Stop."

71
00:09:27,500 --> 00:09:29,627
Good. Father's placing everything
in my hands.

72
00:09:29,802 --> 00:09:32,293
But I haven't finished yet. He also says:

73
00:09:32,471 --> 00:09:35,634
"But don't do anything, just sit."

74
00:09:35,808 --> 00:09:37,207
Let me see that.

75
00:09:37,376 --> 00:09:40,539
Why, Pinky, evidently you've been
in charge of the office before.

76
00:09:40,713 --> 00:09:43,181
- Excuse me. Can you help me in section D?
- What is it?

77
00:09:43,349 --> 00:09:45,146
- I can't do a thing with her, sir.
- Who?

78
00:09:45,318 --> 00:09:47,411
The lady in section D, sir.
She's an American.

79
00:09:47,587 --> 00:09:49,521
You know how these Americans are, sir.

80
00:09:49,689 --> 00:09:52,419
- When finished, look after that gentleman.
- Yes, sir.

81
00:09:52,592 --> 00:09:54,583
Will you gentlemen come with me, please?

82
00:09:56,395 --> 00:09:59,922
Excuse me, madam, I am the chief
inspector. Anything I can do for you?

83
00:10:00,099 --> 00:10:02,363
You most certainly can.

84
00:10:02,535 --> 00:10:04,298
This man wants to mess up my trunks...

85
00:10:04,470 --> 00:10:07,166
...after I've packed the lovely things
I bought in Paris.

86
00:10:07,340 --> 00:10:10,138
I'm very sorry, madam,
but we have to inspect all luggage...

87
00:10:10,309 --> 00:10:12,504
...for dutiable merchandise.

88
00:10:12,678 --> 00:10:15,579
Now, madam, how much
did you pay for this?

89
00:10:15,748 --> 00:10:17,716
That? Oh, now, how much
did I pay for that?

90
00:10:17,883 --> 00:10:21,375
I know I paid an awful lot. But I shouldn't
be telling you that, should I?

91
00:10:21,554 --> 00:10:25,581
- Where did you buy it?
- Where did I buy it? Oh, now, let me see.

92
00:10:25,758 --> 00:10:28,022
What was the name of that town?

93
00:10:29,862 --> 00:10:34,390
- Paris?
- Paris? No. No, it wasn't Paris.

94
00:10:34,900 --> 00:10:37,664
- Lyons?
- No. No, it wasn't Lyons...

95
00:10:37,837 --> 00:10:39,771
...but you're getting warmer.

96
00:10:42,074 --> 00:10:45,441
- Nice?
- Niece. Yes, that's who I'm waiting for.

97
00:10:45,611 --> 00:10:47,977
- What?
- Yes, my niece, Mimi.

98
00:10:48,147 --> 00:10:51,480
I sent her a cable to London
and told her to meet me here.

99
00:10:51,651 --> 00:10:54,449
- Where is she?
- I'm sure I don't know, madam.

100
00:10:56,689 --> 00:10:58,680
This is the only other place
she might be.

101
00:10:58,858 --> 00:11:01,827
Oh, there she is.
Thank you very much.

102
00:11:01,994 --> 00:11:04,394
- Hortense.
- Mimi, dear.

103
00:11:04,563 --> 00:11:06,758
How are you?
Oh, you look perfectly marvelous.

104
00:11:06,932 --> 00:11:08,194
Yes, don't I.

105
00:11:08,367 --> 00:11:10,562
This is my niece, Mimi.
I told you about her.

106
00:11:10,736 --> 00:11:13,000
The poor thing has had her life
all mixed up...

107
00:11:13,172 --> 00:11:16,630
...but I've come over expressly
to straighten it all out for her.

108
00:11:16,809 --> 00:11:20,870
Madam, we would appreciate it
if you'd straighten this matter out first.

109
00:11:21,047 --> 00:11:22,844
Well, what is it you want me to do?

110
00:11:23,015 --> 00:11:26,849
Come with me and we'll make
a declaration of all your purchases.

111
00:11:27,019 --> 00:11:28,452
Everything's so topsy-turvy.

112
00:11:28,621 --> 00:11:30,919
Will you put those things in
while I lock this?

113
00:11:31,090 --> 00:11:32,318
- These?
- Yes, please.

114
00:11:32,491 --> 00:11:35,688
Would you be good enough
to hold this for me? Thank you.

115
00:11:35,861 --> 00:11:38,887
- Did you have a nice trip?
- I had a marvelous trip. I adore Paris.

116
00:11:39,065 --> 00:11:41,431
It's so like Chicago.
I enjoyed every minute of it.

117
00:11:42,001 --> 00:11:45,869
It's such a relief when you're traveling
to feel that you've never left home at all.

118
00:11:49,875 --> 00:11:52,742
I shouldn't be long, dear.
Come along, men.

119
00:12:13,032 --> 00:12:15,398
Porter. Porter.

120
00:12:15,568 --> 00:12:18,594
- Oh, porter.
- Sorry, I'm busy, ma'am.

121
00:12:21,340 --> 00:12:22,932
Porter.

122
00:12:25,411 --> 00:12:28,278
Oh, porter. Porter.

123
00:12:30,583 --> 00:12:31,880
Porter.

124
00:12:34,553 --> 00:12:38,512
Porter. Porter.

125
00:12:39,892 --> 00:12:41,450
Porter.

126
00:12:42,361 --> 00:12:44,989
I beg your pardon.
Can I be of any assistance?

127
00:12:45,564 --> 00:12:47,896
Why... Well, yes.

128
00:12:48,067 --> 00:12:51,366
My aunt is in the inspector's office.
Would you call her for me?

129
00:12:51,537 --> 00:12:52,902
- Well, yes, indeed.
- Thank you.

130
00:12:53,072 --> 00:12:54,539
With pleasure.

131
00:12:57,943 --> 00:13:01,640
- You're an American, aren't you?
- Yes.

132
00:13:02,314 --> 00:13:06,045
- So am I.
- So is my aunt.

133
00:13:06,218 --> 00:13:08,880
You know, the one you were
going to call for me.

134
00:13:09,054 --> 00:13:10,578
Oh, yes.

135
00:13:13,359 --> 00:13:15,657
Is there anything special
you want me to tell her?

136
00:13:17,029 --> 00:13:21,227
Well, you might tell her
that my dress is caught.

137
00:13:22,902 --> 00:13:24,836
Your dress is caught.

138
00:13:26,472 --> 00:13:28,133
My, my.

139
00:13:28,808 --> 00:13:30,833
- Locked.
- Yes.

140
00:13:31,010 --> 00:13:32,602
And you want me to call your aunt?

141
00:13:33,379 --> 00:13:34,937
Yes.

142
00:13:35,981 --> 00:13:38,745
You know, a third party
might spoil this.

143
00:13:38,918 --> 00:13:40,818
Porter. Oh, porter.

144
00:13:40,986 --> 00:13:43,784
Oh, porter. Porter.

145
00:13:44,023 --> 00:13:46,389
There's no reason why I can't
handle this myself.

146
00:13:46,559 --> 00:13:49,027
I pulled a cat out of a well once
when I was a boy.

147
00:13:49,195 --> 00:13:50,924
Now, let me see...

148
00:13:55,067 --> 00:13:58,161
- Maybe I should've called your aunt.
- Well...

149
00:13:58,337 --> 00:14:02,034
Oh, I'm awfully sorry. Please take this.

150
00:14:06,445 --> 00:14:08,379
- Please forgive me.
- I'm living in London.

151
00:14:08,547 --> 00:14:10,242
Where can I return this to you?

152
00:14:10,416 --> 00:14:15,581
Oh, I'm stopping in London too.
May I save you the trouble and call for it?

153
00:14:15,754 --> 00:14:17,722
I'd rather you wouldn't.

154
00:14:19,758 --> 00:14:23,524
Well, here's my address.

155
00:14:24,163 --> 00:14:26,290
I'll be waiting to hear from you.

156
00:14:29,235 --> 00:14:32,136
- You didn't say goodbye.
- No, I didn't.

157
00:14:32,304 --> 00:14:35,205
Well, that's wonderful.
That means I'll see you again.

158
00:14:42,548 --> 00:14:45,415
I'll pay it, but I want to know
how every cent is spent.

159
00:14:45,584 --> 00:14:46,881
Oh, here you are, Hortense.

160
00:14:47,052 --> 00:14:49,043
I just had the most embarrassing
experience.

161
00:14:49,221 --> 00:14:50,688
A man tore my dress off.

162
00:14:50,856 --> 00:14:53,120
My goodness. Anyone we know?

163
00:14:53,292 --> 00:14:56,420
- Hortense.
- Here you are, madam.

164
00:14:56,595 --> 00:15:00,622
Oh, for me? And I do adore fruit baskets.

165
00:15:00,799 --> 00:15:03,791
Oh, isn't he generous.
You shouldn't have been so extravagant.

166
00:15:03,969 --> 00:15:06,733
After all, we've just met, you know.

167
00:15:39,305 --> 00:15:41,739
Not bad. Not bad at all.
Have you time for an encore?

168
00:15:41,907 --> 00:15:45,104
- Sorry, guvnor. My time's too valuable.
- Oh, so sorry.

169
00:15:45,277 --> 00:15:47,404
Don't you want to ask me
who sent that, sir?

170
00:15:47,579 --> 00:15:51,379
Oh, I see, the play spirit.
All right, tell me. Who sent it?

171
00:15:51,550 --> 00:15:55,850
The young lady gave me 3 shillings,
sir, and asked me not to tell.

172
00:15:58,424 --> 00:16:03,452
Oh, yes. I see.
"And asked me not to tell."

173
00:16:06,332 --> 00:16:07,560
- Guy.
- Yeah?

174
00:16:07,733 --> 00:16:09,462
- Package for you.
- A package?

175
00:16:09,635 --> 00:16:12,433
- Yeah.
- Oh, that's my raincoat.

176
00:16:13,539 --> 00:16:14,870
That must be her handwriting.

177
00:16:15,040 --> 00:16:16,905
Let me see.
I used to study handwriting.

178
00:16:17,076 --> 00:16:18,543
- Yeah.
- Oh, it's very neat.

179
00:16:18,711 --> 00:16:21,612
Yes. The O's and the A's are open.
That means extravagance.

180
00:16:21,780 --> 00:16:24,510
Look at the way she crosses her T's.
That denotes temper.

181
00:16:24,683 --> 00:16:29,143
She makes little circles instead of dots.
Dreadful. It's an unfailing sign of vanity.

182
00:16:29,321 --> 00:16:31,881
Yes. Of course, don't let me
discourage you. l...

183
00:16:32,057 --> 00:16:35,754
Guy, what is the matter with you?
You seem to be under some sort of a spell.

184
00:16:35,928 --> 00:16:38,988
I am, and for the first time in my life.

185
00:16:39,231 --> 00:16:40,960
What are you looking for?

186
00:16:41,133 --> 00:16:43,328
- Where's the note?
- Oh, no note.

187
00:16:43,502 --> 00:16:44,935
- No note?
- No note.

188
00:16:45,104 --> 00:16:47,038
- Did you talk to the messenger?
- I did.

189
00:16:47,206 --> 00:16:51,165
And he said that she asked him
not to tell where it came from.

190
00:16:51,810 --> 00:16:54,836
I wonder if she resented
my tearing her skirt.

191
00:16:55,014 --> 00:16:58,006
Well, I wouldn't be at all surprised.
That's the usual reaction.

192
00:16:58,183 --> 00:17:01,209
- What did you do that for?
- She couldn't move.

193
00:17:01,387 --> 00:17:03,912
Sounds very unsporting of you.
Guy, really.

194
00:17:04,089 --> 00:17:07,024
Well, you don't understand.
You see, she... It was an accident.

195
00:17:07,192 --> 00:17:10,787
- It usually is. What's her name?
- I don't know.

196
00:17:10,963 --> 00:17:13,693
- Where does she live?
- I don't know.

197
00:17:13,966 --> 00:17:15,900
My, what an interesting romance.

198
00:17:16,068 --> 00:17:20,471
I was in hopes that she'd send some note
with this raincoat, along with her address.

199
00:17:20,639 --> 00:17:23,437
Well, without having the prophetic powers
of a seventh son...

200
00:17:23,609 --> 00:17:27,067
...I would hazard that she doesn't want
to see you anymore.

201
00:17:28,881 --> 00:17:31,008
Yes. Well...

202
00:17:31,183 --> 00:17:33,845
...I'm going to rush off
to the office.

203
00:17:34,186 --> 00:17:37,849
- What are you going to do, Guy?
- I'm going to start looking for her.

204
00:17:38,023 --> 00:17:40,992
I'll find that girl, Egbert,
if it takes me from now on.

205
00:17:41,860 --> 00:17:46,320
Well, it shouldn't be difficult. After all,
there are only 3 million women in London.

206
00:17:57,776 --> 00:18:03,009
<i>It's just like looking for a needle</i>
<i>In a hay stack</i>

207
00:18:03,182 --> 00:18:05,980
<i>Searching for a moonbeam in the blue</i>

208
00:18:07,319 --> 00:18:10,846
<i>Still, I've gotta find you</i>

209
00:18:13,125 --> 00:18:18,290
<i>It's just like looking for a raindrop</i>
<i>In the ocean</i>

210
00:18:18,464 --> 00:18:22,594
<i>Searching for a dewdrop in the dew</i>

211
00:18:22,768 --> 00:18:26,761
<i>Still, I've got to find you</i>

212
00:18:28,073 --> 00:18:31,907
<i>I'll roam the town</i>
<i>In hopes that we'll meet</i>

213
00:18:32,077 --> 00:18:35,569
<i>Look at each face</i>
<i>I pass on the street</i>

214
00:18:35,747 --> 00:18:39,410
<i>For sometimes I hear</i>
<i>The beat of your feet</i>

215
00:18:40,219 --> 00:18:43,746
<i>But it's just imagination</i>

216
00:18:44,356 --> 00:18:49,589
<i>Oh, it's like looking for a needle</i>
<i>In a haystack</i>

217
00:18:49,761 --> 00:18:53,060
<i>Still, I'll follow every little clue</i>

218
00:18:53,866 --> 00:18:57,962
<i>'Cause I've got to find you</i>

219
00:18:59,771 --> 00:19:05,107
<i>It's just like looking for a needle</i>
<i>In a haystack</i>

220
00:19:05,277 --> 00:19:09,441
<i>Searching for a moonbeam in the blue</i>

221
00:19:09,615 --> 00:19:12,641
<i>Still, I've got to find you</i>

222
00:19:15,287 --> 00:19:20,418
<i>It's just like looking for a raindrop</i>
<i>In the ocean</i>

223
00:19:20,592 --> 00:19:24,926
<i>Searching for a dewdrop in the dew</i>

224
00:19:25,564 --> 00:19:28,692
<i>Still, I've gotta find you</i>

225
00:19:30,402 --> 00:19:34,270
<i>I'll roam the town</i>
<i>In hopes that we'll meet</i>

226
